SIMPLE: mingle
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mingle
<hw>Min"gle</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Mingled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mingling</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[From OE.
<ets>mengen</ets>, AS. <ets>mengan</ets>; akin to D. & G.
<ets>mengen</ets>, Icel. <ets>menga</ets>, also to E. <ets>among</ets>,
and possibly to <ets>mix</ets>. Cf. <er>Among</er>,
<er>Mongrel</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To mix; intermix; to combine or join, as an
individual or part, with other parts, but commonly so as to be
distinguishable in the product; to confuse; to confound.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>There was . . . fire <qex>mingled</qex> with the hail.</q>
<rj><qau>Ex. ix. 24.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To associate or unite in society or by ties of
relationship; to cause or allow to intermarry; to intermarry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The holy seed have <qex>mingled</qex> themselves with the people
of those lands.</q> <rj><qau>Ezra ix. 2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To deprive of purity by mixture; to
contaminate.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A <qex>mingled</qex>, imperfect virtue.</q>
<rj><qau>Rogers.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To put together; to join.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To make or prepare by mixing the ingredients
of.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[He] proceeded to <qex>mingle</qex> another draught.</q>
<rj><qau>Hawthorne.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mingle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mingle
<hw>Min"gle</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To become mixed or
blended.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To associate (with certain people); <as>as, he's too
highfalutin to <ex>mingle</ex> with working stiffs</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To move (among other people); -- of people; <as>as,
the president left his car to <ex>mingle</ex> with the crowd; a host at
a a party should <ex>mingle</ex> with his guests</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mingle</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mingle
<hw>Min"gle</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>A mixture.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mingleable</ent>⟦br⟧
